description.plain:
A$AP Mob is a Harlem-based group and collective founded in 2006 by A$AP Bari, A$AP Illz, and A$AP Yams.

A$AP Mob put out their first mixtape, Lord$ Never Worry, in 2012.

For the next few years, the Mob strove as a collective of independent artists. Meanwhile, the group had to experience Yams' untimely passing in 2015. This likely inspired them to come together for 2016’s Cozy Tapes, Vol. 1: Friends -.

The backronym A$AP has been ascribed various meanings, including “Always Strive and Prosper,” “Assassinating Snitches and Police,” and “Acronym Symbolizing Any Purpose.”

description.plain:
A$AP Rocky of Harlem teams up with Quavo and Playboi Carti of Atlanta, Philadelphia’s Lil Uzi Vert, and LA-based Frank Ocean to deliver this one-of-a-kind banger. With a stacked list of artists, including four of the east coast’s hottest hip-hop talents, “RAF” brings unique verses highlighting each artist’s flair and character.

The hit was premiered on the May 15th on the 6th episode of Frank Ocean’s “blonded RADIO”, and a week later the official song was released on Apple Music on May 22.

The official updated single/album version includes both Frank’s verse from this single version, as well as the verse from “RAF Version 2”.

songs.full_title: Yamborghini High by A$AP Mob (Ft. Juicy J)
songs.title: Yamborghini High

description.plain:
A$AP Mob seize the day and get “Yamborghini High” in honor of their late mastermind, A$AP Yams. Yams founded the Mob with A$AP Bari and A$AP Illz in 2006, managed its label, A$AP Worldwide, and handled A&R and executive production.

In January 2015, Yams passed away at the age of 26. The death was ruled an accidental mixed-drug overdose—the coroner found opiates and Xanax in Yams’ system.

Rocky told the New York Times: “Yams always had a struggle with drugs. That was his thing.” The summer before he died, Rocky and the Mob put Yams in rehab—but he didn’t stay sober for long.

A year after Yams’ death, on what the A$AP mob has dubbed “Yams Day,” the crew unites to pay their respects to their beloved friend for how much he inspired them.

Rocky told MTV:

I lost my brother. I’d trade all this music to have Yams back…Life ain’t good without Yams. He was a visionary. He always had faith in me, even when no one knew what was gonna happen next.

On July 21, The A$AP Mob made its network television debut on The Late Show with Jimmy Fallon, performing the song live.
